name: acidophilic
description: A population growth phenotype that applies to microorganisms whose optimal growth occurs between pH 0 and 5.5.

name: aerotolerant
description: A prokaryotic metabolic quality where the organism grows in the absence of oxygen. Can grow or live in the presence of oxygen.

name: biosafety level
description: A coded value specifying an assessment of the potential risk associated with the handling of the biospecimen.

name: cell color: yellow pigment
description: A colony pigmentation phenotype where colonies are pigmented.

name: cell color
description: A colony pigmentation phenotype where colonies are pigmented.

name: cell length
description: cell length phenotype

name: cell length maximum
description: cell length phenotype

name: cell length minimum
description: cell length phenotype

name: cell shape
description: A cell morphology phenotype where the trait in question is the shape of a cell.

name: cell width
description: cell diameter phenotype

name: cell width maximum
description: cell diameter phenotype

name: cell width minimum
description: cell diameter phenotype

name: coding density
description: a coding sequence is a sequence of nucleotides which encode a RNA or protein product..

name: enzyme activity
description: Enzyme activity finding

name: estimated gene count
description: The counting of features (typically, genes) within aligned sequence data, and organization of these counts into one or more tables.

name: estimated genome size
description: The assembly genome size is the sum of all lengths of a sequence assembly's contigs.

name: flagellum arrangement
description: A flagellum phenotype where the trait in question is the location of the flagellum on an organism.

name: GC percentage
description: The relative amounts of the PURINES and PYRIMIDINES in a nucleic acid.

name: gene count
description: The counting of features (typically, genes) within aligned sequence data, and organization of these counts into one or more tables.

name: genome size
description: The assembly genome size is the sum of all lengths of a sequence assembly's contigs.

name: gram negative
description: A gram stain phenotype where a cell or cells do not retain crystal violet stain when decolorized with an organic solvent such as ethanol.

name: gram positive
description: A gram stain phenotype where a cell or cells retain crystal violet stain when decolorized with an organic solvent such as ethanol.

name: indole test
description: Metabolic test for tryptophanase [L-tryptophan indole-lyase (deaminating)] activity. Measures the formation of indole from tryptophan using the enzyme Tryptophanase. Indole is detected by the addition of Kovac's reagent (isoamy alchohol, para-dimethylaminobenzaldehyde, and concentrated HCl). Indole forms a complex with para-dimethylaminobenzaldehyde, resulting a red color. A negative result is yellow. In some API tests, James' reagent (a proprietary mixture of HCl, water, and 2-methoxy-4-dimethylamino benzaldehyde) is used instead of Kovac's reagent, as it has a longer shelf life. Tryptophanase catalyzes the following reaction: Tryptophan + H2O <=> indole + pyruvate + ammonia

name: methyl red test
description: Methyl red test (procedure)

name: facultative anaerobe
description: A microbial phenotype that describes a microorganism that does not require oxygen gas (O2) for growth but will utilize O2 in metabolic reactions when it is present.

name: obligate aerobic
description: A microbial phenotype that describes a microorganism that requires the presence of oxygen gas (O2) for growth.

name: obligate anaerobic
description: A microbial phenotype that describes a microorganism that does not grow in the presence of oxygen gas (O2).

name: oxygen preference
description: The metabolic quality of a microorganism with respect to its relationship to oxygen.

name: capnophilic
description: Capnophilic bacteria

name: pH growth
description: A population growth phenotype relating to how the rate and/or extent of growth of a microbial population is affected by the pH of the environment.

name: pH maximum
description: A population growth phenotype relating to how the rate and/or extent of growth of a microbial population is affected by the pH of the environment.

name: pH minimum
description: A population growth phenotype relating to how the rate and/or extent of growth of a microbial population is affected by the pH of the environment.

name: pH preference
description: A population growth phenotype relating to how the rate and/or extent of growth of a microbial population is affected by the pH of the environment.

name: presence of hemolysis
description: A hemolysis test phenotype where a cell or cells causes hemolysis.

name: presence of motility
description: A motility phenotype where a microbe possesses the ability to perform controlled self-propelled movement that results in translocation from one place to another.

name: psychrophilic
description: Temperature optimum quality, where growth rates at depressed temperatures (<20˚C) are higher than growth rates at ambient temperatures.

name: salinity growth
description: A population growth range phenotype related to how growth of a microbial population is affected by the concentration of solutes (water activity) in the environment.

name: salinity maximum
description: A population growth range phenotype related to how growth of a microbial population is affected by the concentration of solutes (water activity) in the environment.

name: salinity minimum
description: A population growth range phenotype related to how growth of a microbial population is affected by the concentration of solutes (water activity) in the environment.

name: salinity preference
description: A population growth range phenotype related to how growth of a microbial population is affected by the concentration of solutes (water activity) in the environment.

name: sporulation
description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a spore over time, from its initiation to the mature structure. A spore is a structure that can be used for dissemination, for survival of adverse conditions because of its heat and desiccation resistance, and/or for reproduction.

name: temperature growth
description: A population growth range phenotype related to how growth of a microbial population is affected by the temperature of the environment.

name: temperature maximum
description: A population growth range phenotype related to how growth of a microbial population is affected by the temperature of the environment.

name: temperature minimum
description: A population growth range phenotype related to how growth of a microbial population is affected by the temperature of the environment.

name: temperature preference
description: A population growth range phenotype related to how growth of a microbial population is affected by the temperature of the environment.

name: thermophilic
description: Temperature optimum quality, where growth rates at elevated temperatures (40-85˚C) are higher than growth rates at ambient temperatures.

name: voges-proskauer test
description: Voges Proskauer test (procedure)

name: aerobic catabolization
description: The enzymatic release of energy from inorganic and organic compounds (especially carbohydrates and fats) which requires oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor.

name: aerobic growth
description: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.

name: anaerobic catabolization
description: The enzymatic release of energy from inorganic and organic compounds (especially carbohydrates and fats) which uses compounds other than oxygen (e.g. nitrate, sulfate) as the terminal electron acceptor.

name: anaerobic growth in the dark
description: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.

name: anaerobic growth with light
description: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.

name: anaerobic growth
description: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.

name: assimilation
description: A cellular process consisting of the biochemical pathways by which a living organism synthesizes chemical substances. This typically represents the energy-requiring part of metabolism in which simpler substances are transformed into more complex ones.

name: builds acid from
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of organic acids, any acidic compound containing carbon in covalent linkage.

name: builds base from
description: A cellular process consisting of the biochemical pathways by which a living organism transforms chemical substances. This includes including anabolism (biosynthetic process) and catabolism (catabolic process). Metabolic processes includes the transformation of small molecules, as well macromolecular processes such as DNA repair and replication, protein synthesis and degradation.

name: builds gas from
description: A cellular process consisting of the biochemical pathways by which a living organism transforms chemical substances. This includes including anabolism (biosynthetic process) and catabolism (catabolic process). Metabolic processes includes the transformation of small molecules, as well macromolecular processes such as DNA repair and replication, protein synthesis and degradation.

name: carbon source
description: A series of processes that forms an integrated mechanism by which a cell or an organism detects the depletion of primary carbon sources and then activates genes to scavenge the last traces of the primary carbon source and to transport and metabolize alternative carbon sources such as carbon dioxide or carbonic acid. The utilization process begins when the cell or organism detects carbon levels, includes the activation of genes whose products detect, transport or metabolize carbon-containing substances, and ends when carbon is incorporated into the cell or organism's metabolism.

name: degradation
description: A cellular process consisting of the biochemical pathways by which a living organism breaks down substances. This includes the breakdown of carbon compounds with the liberation of energy for use by the cell or organism.

name: electron acceptor
description: A substance to which an electron may be transferred.

name: electron donor
description: A molecular entity that can transfer an electron to another molecular entity.

name: energy source
description: The chemical reactions and pathways by which a cell derives energy from organic compounds

name: fermentation
description: The catabolic process that includes oxidation-reduction reactions for the generation of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and primarily uses organic compounds as both electron donors and acceptors, without consumption of oxygen.

name: growth
description: The increase in size or mass of an entire organism, a part of an organism or a cell.

name: hydrolysis
description: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of various bonds, e.g. C-O, C-N, C-C, phosphoric anhydride bonds, etc.

name: nitrogen source
description: A series of processes that forms an integrated mechanism by which a cell or an organism detects the depletion of primary nitrogen source, usually ammonia, and then activates genes to scavenge the last traces of the primary nitrogen source and to transport and metabolize alternative nitrogen sources. The utilization process begins when the cell or organism detects nitrogen levels, includes the activation of genes whose products detect, transport or metabolize nitrogen-containing substances, and ends when nitrogen is incorporated into the cell or organism's metabolism.

name: oxidation
description: A metabolic process that results in the removal or addition of one or more electrons to or from a substance, with or without the concomitant removal or addition of a proton or protons.

name: produces
description: A cellular process consisting of the biochemical pathways by which a living organism synthesizes chemical substances. This typically represents the energy-requiring part of metabolism in which simpler substances are transformed into more complex ones.

name: reduction
description: A metabolic process that results in the removal or addition of one or more electrons to or from a substance, with or without the concomitant removal or addition of a proton or protons.

name: required for growth
description: A nutrient is a food component that an organism uses to survive and grow.

name: respiration
description: The enzymatic release of energy from inorganic and organic compounds (especially carbohydrates and fats) which either requires oxygen (aerobic respiration) or does not (anaerobic respiration).

name: sulfur source
description: A series of processes that forms an integrated mechanism by which a cell or an organism detects the depletion of primary sulfur sources and then activates genes to scavenge the last traces of the primary sulfur source and to transport and metabolize alternate sulfur sources. The utilization process begins when the cell or organism detects sulfur levels, includes the activation of genes whose products detect, transport or metabolize sulfur-containing compounds, and ends when the sulfur is incorporated into the cell or organism's metabolism.

name: utilizes
description: A cellular process consisting of the biochemical pathways by which a living organism transforms chemical substances. This includes including anabolism (biosynthetic process) and catabolism (catabolic process). Metabolic processes includes the transformation of small molecules, as well macromolecular processes such as DNA repair and replication, protein synthesis and degradation.

name: nitrogen source: (S)-lactate
description: A series of processes that forms an integrated mechanism by which a cell or an organism detects the depletion of primary nitrogen source, usually ammonia, and then activates genes to scavenge the last traces of the primary nitrogen source and to transport and metabolize alternative nitrogen sources. The utilization process begins when the cell or organism detects nitrogen levels, includes the activation of genes whose products detect, transport or metabolize nitrogen-containing substances, and ends when nitrogen is incorporated into the cell or organism's metabolism.
